<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Distribution and habitat.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Restricted to northwestern Argentina and southwestern Bolivia. Argentina (Jujuy, Salta [expected]), Bolivia (
<normalizedToken originalValue="Potosí">Potosi</normalizedToken>
). It grows in wet meadows and rocky places of the dry puna ecoregion, between elevations of 4600-5200 m (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 20" captionStartId="F20" captionText="Figure 20. Distribution map of Xenophyllum poposa (left hand), X. lorochaqui (right hand, closed triangle), and X. rosenii (right hand, open circle)." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.158.50848.figure20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/448900" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">20</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Xenophyllum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xenophyllum rosenii" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rosenii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophyllum rosenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is hitherto known from very few gatherings, i.e., the type locality in Jujuy (Argentina) plus two collections from southern Sur 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lípez">Lipez</normalizedToken>
(Bolivia). 
<bibRefCitation author="Jorgensen, PM" editor="Jorgensen, PM" journalOrPublisher="Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 127, Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="300 - 301" refId="B19" refString="Jorgensen, PM, 2014. Xenophyllum V.A. Funk. In: Jorgensen, PM, Nee, MH, Beck, SG, Eds., Catalogo de las Plantas Vasculares de Bolivia. Monographs in Systematic Botany from the Missouri Botanical Garden 127, Missouri Botanical Garden Press, St. Louis: 300 - 301" title="Xenophyllum V. A. Funk." volumeTitle="Catalogo de las Plantas Vasculares de Bolivia." year="2014">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jørgensen">Jorgensen</normalizedToken>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
also indicated this species from Oruro (Bolivia) on the basis of a misidentified collection that actually corresponds to 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. digitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="digitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. digitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Liberman 352</emphasis>
, LPB).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="phenology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Collected in flower in March and November.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">It is named after Eric von Rosen (1879-1948), a Swedish aristocrat, explorer, and ethnographer.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Xenophyllum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Xenophyllum rosenii" order="Asterales" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rosenii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Xenophyllum rosenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is unique in the genus by its 2-forked leaves. The species has been confused with 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. digitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="digitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. digitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Meneses 5446</emphasis>
, LPB; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Treviño">Trevino</normalizedToken>
761
</emphasis>
, HSP; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Tupayachi 736</emphasis>
, US). A detailed study of the leaves highlights that these species can be straightforwardly discriminated from one another by the leaf apex (2-forked in 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. rosenii" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="rosenii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. rosenii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vs. 3-forked in 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. digitatum" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" rank="species" species="digitatum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">X. digitatum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The other characters appear to be useless because of a significant overlapping among them.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Since two specimens of the gathering 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Fries 862</emphasis>
were found at UPS, the lectotypification has been further narrowed to a single specimen by way of a second-step lectotype (UPS-V-833144).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
